---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Tech Executives | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for CTOs, VPs of Engineering, and tech executives working internationally, covering executive benefits, global leadership, and board roles.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Tech Executives";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for CTOs, VPs of Engineering, and technology executives leading organizations across global markets.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/tech-executive-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/tech-executive-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'executive-benefits', label: 'Executive Benefits' },
  { id: 'company-types', label: 'Company Types' },
  { id: 'global-leadership', label: 'Global Leadership' },
  { id: 'board-advisory', label: 'Board & Advisory' },
  { id: 'career-transitions', label: 'Career Transitions' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell 
  title={title} 
  description={description} 
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
    
    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International Tech Executive Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Tech executives—CTOs, VPs of Engineering, SVPs, and Chief Product Officers—lead technology strategy and execution at the highest levels. These roles involve significant responsibility, global travel, and substantial compensation. Benefits typically reflect executive status.
      </p>
      <p>
        Executive tech roles span companies from startups to Fortune 500. The demands include board presentations, investor relations, organizational leadership, and strategic decision-making. The pressure is substantial, but so are the resources available.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for tech executives across company types and career stages.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Tech Executives</h2>
      
      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Executive Level?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'Executive health programs', why: 'Leadership demands', typical: 'Usually included' },
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'High-stakes pressure', typical: 'Comprehensive' },
          { need: 'Concierge healthcare', why: 'Time constraints', typical: 'Often available' },
          { need: 'Global coverage', why: 'International travel', typical: 'Standard' },
          { need: 'Family coverage', why: 'Household protection', typical: 'Premium options' },
          { need: 'Disability coverage', why: 'Income protection', typical: 'Often enhanced' },
        ]}
      />
      
      <h3>Executive Compensation</h3>
      <p>
        Tech executives receive substantial compensation packages. Benefits typically match with premium health coverage, executive health programs, and enhanced options. Total compensation enables personal coverage investment if needed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Executive packages often include life insurance, disability coverage, and comprehensive family benefits. Review the full package when evaluating coverage.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Executive Reality</h3>
      <p>
        Tech executive roles involve constant pressure—board expectations, market competition, organizational challenges, and public visibility. Coverage should support managing the unique demands of C-level and VP-level leadership.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="executive-benefits">
      <h2>Executive Benefits</h2>
      
      <h3>Executive Health Programs</h3>
      <p>
        Many companies offer executive health programs—comprehensive annual physicals, preventive screenings, and priority access. These programs catch health issues early and minimize time away from responsibilities.
      </p>
      <p>
        Executive physicals at premium facilities (Mayo Clinic Executive Health, Cleveland Clinic, etc.) may be included or subsidized. Review what your company provides.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Concierge Healthcare</h3>
      <p>
        Some executive packages include concierge healthcare—priority scheduling, extended appointments, and dedicated provider relationships. This addresses the time constraints executives face.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Enhanced Mental Health</h3>
      <p>
        Executive roles create significant mental health demands. Premium coverage often includes enhanced mental health access—executive coaching, therapy, and stress management resources beyond standard plans.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Family Coverage</h3>
      <p>
        Executive packages typically include comprehensive family coverage. Spousal and dependent coverage is usually premium. Review the full family coverage, not just individual benefits.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Tech Executives"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for CTOs, VPs, and tech executives leading global organizations."
      buttonText="Compare Tech Executive Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="company-types">
      <h2>Coverage by Company Type</h2>
      
      <h3>Public Company Executives</h3>
      <p>
        Public company tech executives have the most comprehensive benefits—executive health, D&O insurance, substantial life and disability coverage. Benefits are designed to attract and retain leadership talent.
      </p>
      <p>
        Public company visibility creates additional pressure. Coverage should support managing the demands of public accountability.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Private Company Executives</h3>
      <p>
        Private company executive benefits vary by funding stage and company maturity. Well-funded private companies often match public company benefits. Earlier-stage companies may have equity-heavy compensation with developing benefits.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Startup CTOs and VPs</h3>
      <p>
        Startup executives may have less comprehensive employer benefits, offset by equity compensation. Evaluate the full picture. Personal coverage may supplement employer benefits until the company scales.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="global-leadership">
      <h2>Global Leadership</h2>
      
      <h3>International Travel</h3>
      <p>
        Tech executives travel extensively—customer meetings, global offices, conferences, and industry events. Executive coverage typically includes comprehensive travel coverage. Verify coverage works across your travel destinations.
      </p>
      <p>
        Frequent international travel creates health demands. Coverage should support maintaining health despite constant travel.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Global Team Leadership</h3>
      <p>
        Executives leading global organizations manage across time zones. Early mornings and late nights for global coordination affect health. Coverage should support managing the demands of global leadership.
      </p>
      
      <h3>International Relocation</h3>
      <p>
        Some executives relocate internationally for roles. Expat executive packages typically include premium international coverage. If relocating, verify the full benefits package for your destination.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="board-advisory">
      <h2>Board and Advisory Roles</h2>
      
      <h3>Board Memberships</h3>
      <p>
        Tech executives often serve on boards—their own company's and others'. Board service involves governance responsibility and some travel. Primary employer coverage typically addresses board service, but verify coverage for external boards.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Advisory Roles</h3>
      <p>
        Executives may advise startups, venture firms, or other organizations. Advisory roles usually don't provide benefits. Primary employer coverage typically covers advisory activities.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Between Roles</h3>
      <p>
        Executives between full-time roles may rely on board and advisory income. COBRA extends previous coverage temporarily. Personal coverage provides stability during executive job searches.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-transitions">
      <h2>Career Transitions</h2>
      
      <h3>Executive Job Changes</h3>
      <p>
        Executive job changes involve negotiating benefits packages. Health coverage is typically negotiable at executive levels. Don't accept coverage downgrades when changing roles.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Severance and Transition</h3>
      <p>
        Executive departures often include severance with extended benefits. Negotiate coverage continuation in employment agreements. Understand your coverage during transitions.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Retirement Planning</h3>
      <p>
        Tech executives should plan post-career coverage. Medicare becomes available at 65, but many executives retire earlier. Personal coverage or retirement benefits bridge the gap.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm a CTO at a tech company. Do I need additional coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Executive benefits are typically comprehensive. Review your full package—executive health programs, mental health access, family coverage. You likely have excellent coverage. Personal supplemental coverage may add flexibility but is often unnecessary.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Does my coverage include executive health programs?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Many executive packages include executive health programs. Check your benefits documentation or HR. These programs provide comprehensive annual assessments and preventive care. If not included, you can access executive health programs personally.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I travel internationally constantly. What should I verify?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Executive coverage typically includes comprehensive international travel coverage. Verify coverage works in your frequent destinations. Check evacuation coverage and 24/7 assistance services. International health insurance can supplement if needed.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm at a startup with limited executive benefits. What are my options?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Startup executive benefits vary. Negotiate for better coverage—it's often possible at executive levels. Personal coverage can supplement gaps. Evaluate total compensation including equity, and ensure health coverage is adequate regardless of employer provisions.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm between executive roles. How do I maintain coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            COBRA extends previous coverage for 18 months but can be expensive. Personal coverage provides flexibility during job searches. If you have board/advisory income, personal coverage works well. Don't let coverage lapse during transitions.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I serve on external boards. Are those activities covered?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Primary employer coverage typically covers board service activities. Verify this with your HR or benefits team. Board travel and related activities should be included in executive coverage. D&O insurance is separate from health coverage.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by fully understanding your executive benefits package. Review executive health programs, mental health access, family coverage, and travel provisions. If coverage gaps exist, negotiate improvements or supplement personally.
      </p>
      <p>
        Tech executive roles drive organizational success. Your coverage should support this demanding work—protecting your health through leadership pressure, providing premium care access, and enabling sustained executive performance.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Tech Executive Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for CTOs, VPs, and tech executives leading global organizations."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
